The Looking Glass Self vs. Existential Function of Social

‘The Looking-Glass self’ is a biological pseudo-mechanism that prevents us from truly fulfilling our natural existential function of social. These reactions, natural or not end up setting humans more complex and true relationships back due to the tendency to authenticate a more consumable or pleasurable outward persona. It ends up preventing true connection within our groups, also known as fulfilling our existential function to form true social connections. 

The Looking-Glass self is the biological tendency to rearrange one’s true self into a more socially accepted person. People shape their perceptions of themselves on how other individuals or groups perceive their outward persona. This habit can make an entirely new personality for a person. Changing small or big aspects of someone’s character to then perfect the outermost persona is essentially basing yourself on a lie or reaction. Thus, this persona is inherently fragile, seeing that it can be built up by lies and false persona. This is the explanation for how people nowadays find they’re different around different types of people. Everyone finds a way to adjust to different groups, strangers, authority figures versus friends, and being alone. Different groups require different necessities, whether it be an honest person, a comedian, a supportive friend, a worker, etc. These different necessities are observable to humans. They pick up on these social queues and in turn, adapt to that group. Some people are better than others at this, practically chameleon-like with their ability to jump from group to group and fit in seamlessly. People also find themselves being naturally withdrawn, calm, polite, and the best version of themselves according to the society that specific person was raised in. Another clear distinction of attitude is the reaction of peers versus an authority figure. When a person is amongst peers they trust or feel they can relate to, they relax in turn. Very laid back and calm in response to their surrounding stimuli. Now at the other end of that spectrum is the authority figure. A person’s attitude will become rigid, perfected, and attentive. This is another reaction nobody thinks about, it is drummed into you at an early age and only progresses clearer as one matures. Finally, there’s being alone. This is where all the other relationships combine and form what one perceives as the true ‘them.’ People will combine all of their roles in their lives, or their multiple mirrors formed by their social reaction to determine their true self. In reality, this is solely the culmination of reactions to certain social stimuli and can change based on minute situational alterations. Each of these reactions are all very natural; they are practically reflexes to the masses of people across the world. Some differentiation in mannerisms is obviously common and possible but the majority conforms to their instincts. 

“The existential function of social” is humanity’s unique tendency to be more aware of social surroundings and the meaning of life. It’s the search for the meaning of life but also knowing that they are not likely to find it. There are many subdivisions that apply to this function, such as collection collaboration capacity, individual vs group thinking, and group morals and values. Humanity has the habit of finding a group, a social setting to belong to. This is the “collective collaboration capacity”, an ability in which humans naturally organize themselves within groups and find their places. When people find their groups or those whom they align with, they adapt to group thinking. It becomes a group affair, the exchange of knowledge, habits, cautionary information, and more. This can also implement a routine for group members. The final aspect of this function is conforming to the group’s values, morals, and definition of meaning. When groups find each other, they work together. They help each other piece together aspects of the world into their meanings. Each person’s experience gets put into the group and in turn, affects the final product of the group. The culmination of all of these subgroups within this function has numerous benefits such as taking stress off an individual, helping the mental function of an individual, putting a mind at peace, and having a sense of community for a social creature. When humans are solely individual and have to continuously function alone, this puts stress on the brain. The brain constantly interprets surrounding stimuli and is constantly working to understand and take in everything around them. Being on high alert 24/7 is a huge burden on the brain. This coincides with mental function in the sense that the brain being by itself and taking on that much work continuously will also tire the brain out. Its ability to function, let alone function well, is better within a group. Loneliness tires the brain and body out quickly. The group takes this burden from the individual. Finally, there’s putting the mind at peace from the sense of community. The group helps put the individual’s mind at ease by determining meaning along with giving each group member a sense of purpose and belonging. Since humans are social creatures, they find peace while fulfilling that need. The feeling that they know what they are doing for the group is good and worth it. Meaning is needed to define reality and the group aids that necessity.

The problem with defining oneself based on puzzle-piecing one’s persona only around the reactions to different social settings is that many aspects of a person will get lost. Such aspects include the material self and pure ego. The material self-comprised of physical aspects or possessions that you identify with can be lost in different groups. Those pieces of oneself will deteriorate away, leaving a hole in one’s persona. The other, is pure ego, the soul or essence of a person. This central component of a person is lost when outward perception is the only thing taken into consideration. People will lose these aspects and more to adapt to a group where they feel they belong. Although this is a natural process, it is also a cheat code that eventually can set you back in more complex and developed relationships. Changing small aspects of oneself and then later being more comfortable to then reveal the true desires, opinions, etc. can confuse the dynamic between the individual and the group. Collective Collaboration Capacity being where humans naturally find a place, due to their constructed personality (looking-glass self) can be set back when one adapts to a group or person, the relationship has that honeymoon phase or that start of a friendship, you change small aspects of yourself to better fit with that person or group dynamic. It’s a cheat that ends up pushing you further away from those who can truly become close to you. Because in the end those outward personas become chipped away, leaving the true core of a person’s nature. 

In conclusion, the attempt to form true social connections is hindered by the instinct to form the best outward version of yourself to others. So, people should attempt to disregard their instincts to falsify the outside and be their truest selves. Let the culmination of their other selves beyond the looking-glass self shine.

Why White Privilege Still Exists in the United States
	Do all lives matter? One may answer, without hesitation, and out of the goodness in their heart, “Yes, of course they do”. However, ask a black American who avoids certain neighborhoods in fear of being harassed and killed in the year of 2021 what they think. Ask any member of a Native American tribe, that is still alive and active today, and living on a reservation what they think. Ask the Mexican American children who are separated from their parents because ice arrested them, what they think? To say all lives matter would imply that there is equal respect and care for citizens of every race. Yet, there is not and there never was. At least not in the United States. 
It may be hard to believe that racial injustice as we all learned about in history class is still occurring even though we may not experience it personally. Even so, it is unfair to discredit racial minorities and claim that they are not oppressed if one is not aware of it. Therefore, the statement, “all lives matter” is an invalid one that does not allow for racial minority groups to speak up about their issues and educate the public. Whether the protests are peaceful with sadness or violent with anger, the feelings of oppressed groups are still valid. The root behind most issues facing minority groups in the United States is race and the existence of White privilege. Throughout this essay, I will further explain what White privilege is, its’ origin in the United States of America, the ways in which it is still present today and how it puts racial minority groups at a societal disadvantage.
White privilege refers to the societal bias set towards White citizens. Being a white U.S citizen means that there is a systematic advantage to ensure that white people are being given first priority for most aspects in life. This may mean being hired over a person of color regardless of job qualifications, being the majority race at an institution due to historical segregation and racial biases, and having politicians and laws cater solely to one’s own demographic. Such things create cases of injustice for people of color who have been subject to lesser opportunities and un-deservingness. 
Racism is a motive behind white privilege as most white Americans may fear that the progression of rights and opportunities for another racial group or demographic may mean less for them. Therefore, as long as wealthy, white citizens have been in a position of power, they have been able to restrict the number of rights and power given to people of color. Simply put, systemic racism created white privilege, and white privilege enforces oppression on other racial groups. The problem is that this issue has existed for as long as the U.S has existed. Therefore, we as a society have to dissect how racism became institutionalized and identify the ways that these practices have evolved with time.
In the United states, race has always been heavily distinguished. One was either white or “colored”. Even as a person of color, some individuals experienced more humane treatment with being visibly “white passing”. A clear indicator of racial privilege is the way in which ethnically ambiguous people were able to bypass racial discrimination. In being a racially divided nation, there was a lack of education on different cultures. Therefore, society functioned off of their knowledge on ignorance and stereotypes. 
The United States was built on colonization and racial division. According to the Stanford Encyclopedia, colonialism is, “a practice of domination, which involves the subjugation of one people to another...colonialism usually involved the transfer of population to a new territory, where the arrivals lived as permanent settlers while maintaining political allegiance to their country of origin” (Kohn, Margaret; Reddy, Kavita 2017). The issue mentioned in the definition here is that colonialism shares similarities with imperialism which involves taking over and taking command of. The similar trait between colonialism and imperialism is that it involves political and economic control over a dependent territory.
Not only were European settlers colonizing indigenous lands, but they were also taking control over the indigenous people. This practice instilled a supremacist mindset as European migrants used dominance to enforce their culture on other ethnic groups. White supremacy is the mindset and belief that white people are the superior race. This mindset controlled who the U.S government felt was deserving and undeserving of certain rights. Therefore, first priority and privilege were granted to white citizens.
The early European settlers went on to force the Native American tribes to either conform to a Eurocentric lifestyle or to live in designated terrain so not to interfere with the settlers. This portion of U.S history instilled the belief that Native Americans were living incorrectly and that they were “savages”. Thousands of Native people were killed and subject to live within specified parameters on their own native continent. In prioritizing the European settlers over the native people, it left an eternal stain on the way in which our country operates today. Native reservations continue to decrease in size and lose access to clean water as the United States Government takes more of the land for construction and oil pipelines. 
Another historical event that influenced race and led to white privilege is slavery. The enslavement of African people further supported the idea of white supremacy because it permitted settlers and early white citizens to treat black people as animals and objects. Black people were chained up like prisoners, bought and sold like cattle, separated from their loved ones, starved, and physically abused. Some received a very small compensation to buy themselves out of slavery with time and others were only compensated with another day of life. Those who escaped slavery were hunted down and returned to slavery or sometimes even killed.  Slavery created this idea that it was necessary to punish black people and limit their rights so that they could not live a life of equal quality to that of white people. Even following the abolishment of slavery, black Americans continued to be beaten, wrongfully imprisoned and lynched as “free” U.S citizens.
 In discussing Jim Crow and the civil rights movement, it is apparent that in the 20th century, black people were still being treated unfairly. They were forced to attend segregated churches, schools, and restaurants. There were, and still are many individuals who do not feel that black people, or POC in general are deserving of a qualitative life. Therefore, cases of implementing white privilege continue to occur and will not cease until they are called publicly acknowledged and parties are held accountable. 
Knowing the origins of racial discrimination and white supremacy provides a foundation for understanding institutionalized racism and white privilege. The article, Raciontologies: Rethinking Anthropological Accounts of Institutional Racism and Enactments of White Supremacy in the United States explains the concept of racism in both the individual and institutional sense. The article favors the belief that racism in the United States is an institutionalized issue. It states that racism is a ‘system of structural inequalities’ and a ‘historical process’”. The article makes note of the fact that the racial conflict that racial minorities face today started during the colonial times and has not ceased but instead evolved. The author references Avram Bornstein in explaining that, “patterns in housing policies that (re)produce segregation and socioeconomic stratification, as well as education policies that structure school funding in relation to local property taxes and impose high‐stakes assessments. In all of these cases, “‘institutional policies operate with or without conscious or unconscious bias, although there is a reinforcing connection between the two’”. 
In observing the existence of white privilege today, A modern example of white privilege is prevalent in politics. As mentioned in the article White Privilege, White Poverty: Reckoning with Class and Race in America. The article uses the 206 presidential election to explain the mindset behind those who still enforce a white supremacist and white privilege mindset. During former president Donald Trump’s campaign, he tried to promote the idea of restoring a “great America” in creating more job opportunities for U.S citizens while simultaneously removing illegal immigrants who were “stealing” these job opportunities away. Trump’s election generated four years of meritocracy. With white Americans being the majority population, such ideals seemed only to benefit their demographic. The wealthy and the white working class. Furthermore, it established a period of blatant hatred towards people of color as they were the targeted out to be the obstacle for the success of white Americans. The article explained it as being “social status anxiety” and “racialized economics” which is the fear of one’s own demographic falling behind with the progression of another demographic (Blacksher, Valles 2021). Therefore, the election and time period following brought attention to the fact that citizens based their presidential vote on personal advantage and that white Americans and politicians purposefully sought out to suppress minority groups. Therefore, reinforcing institutionalized racial prejudice.
In sending ICE to track down “illegal immigrants”, a stigma was created against Mexican Americans. In not openly supporting the Black Lives Matter movement, supporters of former president Donald Trump disapproved with the movement and protested against it labeling protestors and supporters as “thugs “in the president’s words. His responses alone, as a white person in power is enough to influence his followers to inflict disdain towards ethnic minority groups. This disdain translates into action when laws and decisions are made in favor of white people and against people of color ultimately permitting white privilege.
A second modern day example would be in healthcare. Racial health disparities are the differences in statistics between white and nonwhite individuals with mortality, health insurance coverage and access to healthcare facilities. The article, An Empirical Analysis of White privilege, Social Position and Health discuses a study done on predominantly White neighborhoods of differently social class. The purpose behind the study was to determine if there was a correlation between health and inequality. The speculation comes from the fact that predominantly white neighborhoods typically have access to healthful resources while black neighborhoods feature sources that are detrimental to one’s health such as liquor stores and even fast-food chains. Therefore, the experiment done through survey questions, would determine if predominantly white neighborhoods experienced better health on the basis of economic status and neighborhood diversity. 
The study found that in some respects there was a decreased welcome for black residents in the neighborhoods when it came to having high dentalcare and healthcare (Kwate, Goodman 2014). The article concluded that in doing the experiment, participants form the lesser diverse neighborhoods may not have answered truthfully about how welcoming their neighborhood would be towards black people due to their personal knowledge on how likely it realistically is for a black family to move in. Furthermore, the question of whether the participants were answering because they and their neighbors acknowledge the existence of racism is still questionable. The experiment not only showed the prominence of better healthcare for racially exclusive communities, but also that there is ignorance on the part of the white neighbors in terms of how welcoming their neighborhoods are to black people, given that there was only a small population of black people living in each of the neighborhoods.
Acknowledgement is a crucial part in abolishing white privilege because it first brings the issue to light and allows those involved to put a stop to it. As Peggy McIntosh mentions in White Privilege: Unpacking The Invisible Knapsack, “As we in Women’s Studies work to reveal male privilege and ask men to give up some of their power, so one who writes about having white privilege might must ask, “having described it, what will I do to lessen or end it?” (McIntosh 1988). It is not enough for people of color to speak out on their own struggles. It is crucial for white citizens as well to hold themselves and their peers accountable. For as long as the United States has dealt with racism and the existence of white privilege, it is evident that the issue needs to be addressed from the inside. As Dr. McIntosh explains, while they were not being actively racist, they grew up unaware of how society catered to them as a white individual. By simply educating oneself and passing the same information along, white citizens can help advance and secure the social rights for POC. This would guarantee them fair opportunities at improved physical health, education, job opportunities and overall safety. This country was originally designed with only White people in mind; therefore, the former laws and practices have become outdated with the increasingly diverse population. U.S citizens of all ethnic backgrounds must share the collective effort of speaking out on racial discrimination and holding oneself accountable for benefiting off of racial privilege if we want to coexist in a peaceful America.

AI Takeover 
	Technology is on the rise in today’s modern world, aiming to conquer and work its way deeper into the everyday lives of human beings. There will always be technological advancements in the works. Whether those are the brand new smartphones expected to hit stores, a smart home that can fully function on its own, or self driving and flying vehicles. But as Apple continues to release a brand new phone every year, and Dubai now only has to perfect their already mastered idea of a self-flying helicopter, there is an even bigger advancement that also grows by time: Artificial Intelligence. Artificial Intelligence or AI has in fact been around for quite some time. Behind doors, scientists experiment, build, and test new structures including AI’s in order to release them into the world. Artificial Intelligence is being designed to properly mimic and recreate algorithms in everyday functions of humans. AI’s take science, formulas, chemical makeups, and neurological discoveries into consideration in order to replicate the basic functions necessary, and then work to expand those with hopes of mastering them. Many people applaud the possibility of artificial intelligence. AI’s can offer a high quality of help and aid in basic tasks they are programmed for. As AI’s can be deemed helpful, there is still a threat they pose to the evolving world. If artificial intelligence systems are allowed to grow into most societies, the need for work performed by regular humans will no longer be a necessity, leading to a world that can be controlled and ruled by engineered intelligence.  With AI’s invading the routine system society has made for themselves, issues are bound to occur, even if artificial intelligence systems could improve areas significantly. 
	When it comes to artificial intelligence systems, people automatically think robots. Although robots are a large part of AI’s, there is a much more complex and intricate network to the AI name. Artificial intelligence is the promising replication of human thoughts and interactions that will be incorporated into AI systems used to take the place of human beings. Areas such as the workforce, government, medical fields, and basic everyday life will soon be affected by the rise of artificial intelligence if not done so already. Behind the scenes of AI systems are often not considered. In order for these AI’s to be brought to life, scientists must figure out how to master the Polyheirarchich Model of Intelligence as described in Keith Stearne’s article “The Polyheirarchich Model of Intelligence: A Critique of the Future of Intelligence Biological and Artificial.” Stearne states that the way scientists have previously been creating these complex systems is through general strategic coordination which is achieved through “the mechanism of a ‘zone of highest general connectivity’ which moves round the strategic region, partly under the direction of the appetitive system, providing the necessary extra input to trigger selected potential responses in the motorium to the current sensory input” (Stearne 158). Scientists have to first figure out how the human brain functions, and responds to actions and demands. With that knowledge a similar electronic system must be created and then programmed to act the same way. As this is the basis for artificial intelligence, scientists must follow up and incorporate feelings and other human functions in order to properly replicate human functionality. Yuval Noah Harari, an Israeli historian, notes in his book 21 Lessons for the 21’st Century that society “usually [fails] to realize that feelings are in fact calculations, because the rapid process of calculation occurs far below our threshold of awareness” (Harari). Once again scientists must come to properly understand the way the body and mind functions, including when dealing with emotions and other important human ideals. Overall it comes down to the mastering of biology and anatomy before artificial intelligence can properly be mastered to where it is authentic and useful. 
	In the world of science, artificial intelligence has always peaked raging interest. As the years go on, the idea of an artificially intelligent world is starting to appeal to everybody. According to Joshue Eckroth in his article “Evolution of a Robust Artificial Intelligence System: A Case Study of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence’s AI-Alert” even “the popularity of #artificialintelligence Twitter hashtag has grown so much that now AITopics’ news content is strongly dominated by stories posted on Twitter” (Eckroth 27). This shows that the idea of artificial intelligence is on people's minds, and growing popular by the minute. The appeal is the general idea of what AI’s can do. In the article “Human Digital Thought Clones: The Holy Grail of Artificial Intelligence for Big Data” written by Jon Truby and Rafael Brown, it is expressed “When humanity’s unquenchable thirst for understanding human behaviour, decision making, and the human mind are coupled with economic incentives, the idea of a digital thought clone is not surprising” (Truby & Brown 167).  It is the general idea of a different and technological society that draws the public into praising and recommending the increase in AI’s. As interesting as the idea of robots running around Earth, and functioning the way humans do is, people must look at the future outcome of supporting the rise of artificial intelligence before fully supporting it. 
	There are a lot of speculations regarding the future of artificial intelligence. As there is no sure outcome of what could come out of the widespread use of AI systems, the possibilities should still be heavily considered. For starters, “An individualised digital thought clone can be used first to predict how a person would behave in a given set of parameters based on very precise behavioural patterns” (Truby & Brown 147). The human mind has already been studied enough for scientists to mimic the functionality into intricate softwares. With knowledge of the human behavioral patterns and how the human mind reacts to certain situations, the basic human algorithm can be completely replicated to where future generations could be shaking hands with robots that will easily be mistaken for real human beings. Eckroth states in his article that “AI algorithms and models trained by ML are often highly tuned to the specific nature of the data on which the algorithm was developed and model was trained” (Eckroth 25). What Eckroth is telling us is that AI’s have been and will continue to be created for specific reasons and for tackling certain objectives. In the future, an AI could easily be created for anything desired, which will eventually work its way into the workforce and take important tasks from real human beings. 
Yuval Noah Harari describes the future of AI’s best. Dedicating half a chapter to the current and future development of artificial intelligence, Harari notes how “Once AI makes better decisions about careers and perhaps even relationships, our concept of humanity and of life will have to change” (Harari). The way society will need to function in the future will soon revolve around AI technology. So much that Harari also states “When the biotech revolution merges with the infotech revolution, it will produce Big Data algorithms that can monitor and understand my feelings much better than I can, and then authority will probably shift from humans to computers” (Harari). If artificial intelligence continues to grow more popular, the future might be strictly run off of AI systems in mostly AI environments. This is not as beneficial or amazing as it seems. As the work put into designing such systems is ordinary and interesting, the increase of a computerized society can give the government more ways to control us. Harari says “As algorithms come to know us so well, authoritarian governments could gain absolute control over their citizens..” (Harari). If the book Nineteen Eighty-Four has ever been read, the future of AI systems can be compared to what George Orwell wrote. A computer could eventually be used to monitor everyday actions, thoughts, and words from citizens. This type of control is exhausting and violates privacy that citizens are promised in the U.S Constitution. But the possibility of a ‘Big Brother’ scenario due to AI’s taking over society is not the only problem that could be faced.
Every artificial intelligence system starts somewhere. A team or specialist has to be the one to make the effort to bring one of these ideas to life. What if the one in control means harm? The AI to come from a creator with mal intention will start numerous issues and pose a risk to mankind. According to Harari, “The real problem with robots is not their own artificial intelligence, but rather the natural stupidity and cruelty of their human masters” (Harari). As AI’s start to populate more than ever, people need to be aware of the bad that can come from the wrong hands. If AI’s can be programmed to be useful, they can most definitely be programmed to cause harm and fear. “Any AI system that processes human generated content must be carefully watched because people will often find ways to influence the system” says Joshua Eckroth (Eckroth 27). There will always be somebody with the mal intention of harming society. This gives them a sense of power and supreme priority over others. If systems can be hacked now, then AI systems can risk being hacked as well. It could only take one bad person to create an AI that will endanger society, and there will not be a way to know that until it is too late. As Keith Stearne says in his article, “we could never know for sure whether or not intelligent beings we create ‘self-aware’ as we are, especially if their construction is radically different from our own” (Stearne 157). Scientists may be able to understand the human genome well enough to replicate it, but once AI’s start to populate, there won’t be enough knowledge from regular citizens to notice wrong behavior fast enough to stop it. They most likely won't know how to stop it. Not only would this increase the risk of harm, but it can also lead to many other complications. Harari believes “the philosophical algorithms will never be perfect. Mistakes will still happen, resulting in injuries, deaths, and extremely complicated lawsuits” (Harari). On top of injuries and pain, AI’s can lead to possible lawsuits that will stress out and mess up a lot of people's lives. Lives of people who might not have wanted or approved for AI’s to be so heavily incorporated into everyday life, either. If the strength of the argument for Artificial Intelligence increases, it could potentially end up that artificial cloning of one person will slowly become less of a choice, and more of a demand. Keith Stearne also makes a point to say that he personally would not be happy if a replica of himself were cloned and created into an AI (Stearne 157). The arguments against the increasing popularity of AI systems are powerful, but it would be wrong to ignore the potential benefits.
As Harari mainly talks about the downfalls of an artificially intelligent future, he also brings up some good viewpoints on how society can be benefitted from AI systems. He starts off by saying “there is no reason to assume that algorithms won’t be able to outperform the average human even in ethics” (Harari). It is no secret that when given the chance, AI systems can and will outperform humans in the work given. This is the biggest argument for Artificial Intelligence, as it does limit the possibility for work that will not be completed to its fullest potential. It can also limit labor costs as AI’s can handle more than one person's work at a time, but it is important to note that this will take away possible jobs for people who need them. Another interesting argument Harari brings up, is that AI’s could reduce discrimination in scoeities. “If we allow a computer to evaluate job applications, and program the computer to completely ignore race and gender, we can be certain that the computer will indeed ignore these factors” (Harari). The idea of programming and using AI’s to ignore race and gender when making decisions will indeed limit the amount of dicrimination that takes play currently. Harari also compares AI systems to the future of war. By replacing soldiers with AI robots, the main goal of a soldier will be carried out proficiently with little error. By error, Harari is talking about the previous cases where soldiers have not been able to control their rage and go off on unnecessary killing and rape sprees. “Since robots have no emotions, they could be trusted to always adhere to the dry letter of the military code, and never be swayed by personal fears and hatred” (Harari). By using robots in these settings, there would be limited defiance and risk of violent outbursts that will negatively impact the world.
It is hard to hear about the incorporation of AI’s into everyday life and side against it. These technological advancements have the potential to do good in society, but when weighing all the negative outcomes to the positive ones, it is clear that a future mostly run by AI’s is not a future worth encouraging. There is too much of a risk of a controlled world that will come from the increase in AI usage and demand. People could also end up hurt in irreversible or non-curable ways. AI’s could also lose control any minute with no way of knowing how to properly handle those situations. AI’s could even be programmed to negatively lose control and harm others. In the end, it is better for society to continue to operate with manual labor as done now. If freedom is promised in the land of America, the threat to our freedom and privacy should be annihilated. Artificial intelligence systems should not be allowed to take control of the world.

Second Graded Essay

	When reading and understanding “The Cultural Logic of Collective Representations Durkheim'' and realizing humans have this collective consciousness might be a little intimidating for some. So in the reading “The Matrix of Domination” thinking white people look at African American women as being a subordinate: do you think this just happened naturally? Or was it a societal thought which evolved into collective consciousness. 
	“By objectifying African American Women and recasting our experiences to serve the elite white men, much of the Eurocentric masculinist fosters Black women's subordination”. To think white people have been taught to look down upon another sex as less than but a race also might not sit well with most Americans. While these not only women but men were oppressed in history on disgusting levels we have to understand why? This happened because of something bigger. I'm not talking about physically enslaving people to gain wealth but let's look into the brain. 
	In “The Cultural Logic of Collective Representations Durkheim” we learned a quick overview of collective consciousness. This has caught my attention on every reading, lecture and essay we have done at some point. Racism is taught. Prejudice is taught. Hate is mostly taught, because I feel you can develop hatred feelings towards things later once the brain has developed. What i'm trying to say in all of this is our collective consciousness has been the downfall of civilization since we can recall. Surveillance in Relation to Human Behaviors
Have you ever felt like you were being watched through your technological devices? Most individuals who live in America use a wide variety of electronics and most of the devices include some type of surveillance. In today’s world of technology advancements, it is a common feeling for tech users to sense they are being watched constantly and almost always under some type of surveillance. Foucault proposed an experiment in a prison that allowed him to focus on prisoners and their behaviors through a control mechanism. I argue that surveillance has a strong connection with the behaviors of humans. The monitoring presence can even control the way people act in a negative way.
Surveillance monitors are found in numerous different types around the world in a variety of locations. One of the most common examples of monitors is security cameras. Security cameras are found in almost all grocery stores, banks, parking decks and common spaces. The cameras can be visible to the human eye or completely hidden. Homeowners have access to purchase house cameras for the inside and outside of their home. The cameras specialized for a home can be created to connect to an iPhone, they can be wired directly into a house, be wireless or battery powered. Computers, iPhones, and cars are also monitors that are connected to a camera of some sort. 
Cameras can be super beneficial and helpful in some cases. For example, cameras are useful in places of business if stealing occurs. The recordings from the cameras are often used as evidence for police officers in many different situations. Most security cameras can also pick up on voices in the recordings. Customers who are aware that cameras are in an area of a store may act different or try to conform to normal actions because they realize they are being watched. A con that elaborates on this example could be that the customers are conforming to the norm and not showing their true personality since they are on camera.
 Another large issue that exists with the significant amount of security cameras being installed is that people no longer have privacy in their lives. Humans are constantly being watched on surveillance in some way, shape or form. I have experienced a form of surveillance in my personal life with my smart phone. One day I was shopping in Old Navy, and I found a sweater that I wanted to purchase. The second I walked outside of the store and looked on my Facebook account there was an Old Navy ad on my page for the exact same sweater that I had just purchased. I immediately felt like I was being watched and that people were listening to me speak as I shopped and looked around the store. I have experienced several other incidents like this story with ads popping up on my computer of the exact same item that I previously had searched for. 
Do you ever wonder where the idea of surveillance becomes too much? Adults and teenagers can be spied on through their cameras on the technological devices that they use. I find it very creepy and invasive that people can watch us at any given time. An article online mentioned that trackers can collect data about a user. The data can include the users phone number, email address, street address and the IP address that is connected to the Internet. Trackers are even able to access the precise location of a user. The information that trackers can find is very personal therefore it is frightening that they are able to easily get into human’s phones. 
Behaviors of people change when they feel like they are being watched. Surveillance over abnormal behavior is one of the topics we focused on in Sociology. Studies have shown that people may try to change their behaviors to fit what the social norms are when they are under surveillance. People also may try to act more kind than they usually are because they are wanting to make a good impression to the people who are watching them. 
Social media makes it very accessible for people to play different roles and to not show their true self and who they are in real life. Many social media platforms create negativity because they portray images that seem to be perfect, and all put together. Their images were created with filters to cover up all their imperfections and it only shows a highlight reel of their daily life. This connects to the idea of being different from expectations constituting a ground for punishment. Many people are worried that if they stand out or look different then they will be put down and made fun of. 
	Social media influencers are a great example of a person trying to change their behaviors to fit a social norm. Influencers spend a generous amount of time picking out different outfits, finding locations to take pictures and planning out their next Instagram post or Tik-tok video that they are going to create. People who are influencers on Instagram or YouTube often change their self-identity to represent for a brand so that they can make money. Privacy can be difficult to achieve for people who are social media influencers because in order to influence people you must show your life to the world. Influencers post blogs and videos that go into many details about their personal life. Hackers are also more likely to be able to get influencers information because in most cases their accounts are made public so they attract a higher amount of viewers. 
	Video surveillance is also used to show abnormal behaviors. Abnormal behaviors can be behaviors that are described as uncultured or different than the normal standard behavior. A term that explains this particular behavior would be “deviance”. Deviance can be defined as a behavior that does not conform to norms and expectations. Society is often so afraid to act in a way that does not fit the social norms. Many people believe that every person should dress the same way, have the same style, and act the same. Deviance can change depending on what activities and interests become popular for a specific year or what is relevant to culture. Finally, deviance is determined by the social context that it is used in. 
Surveillance is predominantly used to control the behaviors of people. Behaviors that are being watched can become more under control in a way. Foucault experienced behavior control through the experiment that he proposed. A “controlling mechanism” is a sophisticated way of describing Foucault’s theory that he experienced through observing the prison. The design technique that was instilled in the prison was called “Panopticon.” This layout forced the prisoners to be spread out and away from each other. While the experiment was taking place there was no time for communication or interacting with others. During the experiment the guards of the prison were able to see inside each cell because they were centered at a tower that had a high viewpoint. The entire experiment allowed Foucault to focus on systems of social control and people in disciplinary situations and how they react. Lastly, he was able to study the “power-knowledge concept.”
Foucault describes the “power-knowledge concept” as, the more a person observes a particular situation the more knowledge they will gain. Therefore, having more knowledge and background information about a circumstance can make people feel like they have more power. He also found through his experiment that there is a penetration of power that comes through to individuals. While there are many mechanisms for observation of humans, power definitely becomes more systematic as more knowledge is gained. Oppression also is a fear that is in place when only specific groups of people understand knowledge. Most people like to find out who is watching them on a camera or even who is listening to the recordings. Knowing who is watching people can make humans feel like they know who is in control and they can understand which people have authority and power. 
Power can be a difficult topic to speak about for humans because we do not always have control and authority over our lives. Most people have probably been in a situation in their life where they felt as if they had no control over a circumstance. This feeling can be uncomfortable, scary, sad and can even cause anxiety for many people. While the idea of surveillance over humans lives is not going to dissapear it is important that people realize they do not have to conform to the norms of society. Our whole scope of our life can be potentially under watch but we can still have originality and a want to be different than others and to stand out in life. 
In conclusion, surveillance strongly relates to the behaviors and the way people act when they are being watched. Being different from what is expected can often constitute grounds for punishment, but it does not always have to be this way. Society has made surveillance over behaviors a normal and accepted part of life. People are so used to being under surveillance, being watched and conforming to the norms of society that it is so comfortable for them. Often people want to do exactly what other people are doing because they fear trying something new and possibly failing at meeting the standards of society. They also may be scared to dress differently or to behave in a way that most people do because other people may not accept them. I would like to challenge the readers to standout, make a difference in the world and try to not conform to the ways of the world. Strive to show positivity in your daily life because negativity can be tiring and draining to you and the other people around you. Always remember that it is beneficial to show others kindness, love others and to not let surveillance control your life behaviors in a negative way.

High School and Conflicts with Feminism
Although many people like to claim that feminism belongs in the past, there are many legitimate reasons why fighting for women’s rights is a current and pressing issue. This discrimination starts young and continues to affect women throughout their lives. As a high school student, I want to discuss how stereotypes and bias influence young women enrolled in secondary schools. From a young age, girls are taught to be ashamed of their bodies and are shamed for using their power to assist themselves and others. Women are kept from working with each other towards a common goal. 
           Before diving into the sociological concepts that explain the prevalence of hegemonic masculinity and the toxic putting-down of young women, I need to explain my own experiences within an institution in my school. For all four years of high school, I have been a part of the Women’s Empowerment through Education, or WEE, club. For the past two years, I have served as secretary of the school. Since I am very involved in this operation, and have been for quite some time, I have experienced many different types of discrimination. I have witnessed both men and women inside and outside the organization shame the club and put it down.
           The first example I would like to speak of involves a feminine product drive that WEE Club put on, in partnership with a feminist club at another nearby high school. This drive was advertised as a feminine product drive and the posters listed the items that the club would be collecting. This included bras, tampons, pads, underwear, and other items for feminine hygiene. The plan was for all these items to be donated to a domestic violence shelter. Our advertiser hung up the posters and was called to the principal’s office, along with our president. 
They were told that we were not allowed to use certain words and descriptions in our advertising because of their “graphic nature.” WEE club was ordered to take down all our signs as well as our donation boxes until we would change the posters to include less inflammatory language. Our principal argued that words such as tampon and bra would distract the young men in our school. He argued that boys may not have been introduced to the concept of a period, and therefore the language we were using was harmful. Since our club focused on feminism and women’s empowerment, we fought back against this censorship. This refusal to change our wording caused the donation drive to be shut down completely. In comparison, our sister club was able to continue the fundraiser with the same wording as us. 
One of the issues surrounding how young women are treated in high school is the ideas and opinions of the men surrounding them. Hegemonic masculinity creates in men the idea that women are weaker and less than. These ideas are approved by the continuous belief in hegemonic masculinity. Male teachers and administrative officers perpetuate the standard by treating female students differently than male ones. Because of the prevalence of hegemonic masculine ideas, types of harmful beliefs have bled into the collective consciousness. This incorrectly displays the thought that men are dominant, and women are subservient. A high school is a dangerous place because it is where these ideas become embedded in the minds of young students, both male and female.
Simone de Beauvoir discusses many of the concepts that I will be discussing in her article titled “Woman as Other.” In this article the author debates how women are thought of as secondary to men, and what, if anything, can be done to combat this. De Beauvoir discusses how because a woman has ovaries and a uterus, she is inferior and subject to rule by the male. Men see their bodies and anatomy as normal and even empowering, whereas a woman’s body is a prison. 
           Simone de Beauvoir’s theory of women as others as well as the theory of hegemonic masculinity, explains my story of the principal banning the use of words such as period or tampon because it might harm young men’s learning and thought processes. In this scenario, the principal thinks that he and his anatomy are superior and the baseline for how all bodies work. This explains his condescending behavior and belief that speaking or writing about menstrual cycles is inappropriate for a school setting. Speaking of bras and tampons breaks down the mental barrier of thought that creates the idea that women are held back by their anatomy. 
            Although I have witnessed and experienced discrimination based on sex by men, there are also many situations where the club faced barriers from other women. I would like to focus on a conflict with our teacher sponsor. Unfortunately, between my junior and senior year, our former teacher sponsor left the school and our club. My school is small, so we were left with a limited number of teachers to choose. We wanted a female representative that would be able to assist us and relate to our mission. We found a new female teacher representative and began my senior year. This female teacher was quite hard to work with and opposed us at every move. At the start of the year, we held meetings in her classroom, and she would argue with us the entire time. She fought against our feminist values and refused to help us in our mission to gain equality for all genders. Because of this teacher, we started losing members, and by the time the first semester had passed, we barely had any people attending our meetings. 
           Although this was annoying and unnecessary, the board was prepared for opposition. However, we were not prepared for what was going to happen next. Our teacher sponsor started trying to shut down our club because she did not believe in our mission or effectiveness. She talked with the principal without informing us and then shut down tbe club for a semester until we could “get our act together.” Our board tried everything from scheduling a meeting with the principal to holding meetings without the authority of our teacher sponsor, but we kept getting shut down. This is a prime example of how other women can oppose modern feminism and cause internal conflict within a movement. 
           This story concerning the teacher sponsor who tried to shut down the club can be explained through defensive othering and inequality between women. This is all discussed in the article titled “Barbie Dolls on the Pitch” by Matthew Ezzell. Ezzell discussed how in defensive othering, a person who is part of a devalued and discriminated group thinks that although certain stereotypes do belong to the group that they are a part of, they do not fit into the same characteristics. They use these thoughts to put themselves on a pedestal while perpetuating the stereotypes that have been forced onto the rest of the group. 
           Ezzell’s article discussing hetero sexy fit and defensive othering play into women devaluing women in many ways. Our teacher sponsor saw that our club was beginning to struggle. Instead of focusing on working with the members and the board to improve the current conditions, she shed her identity as a fellow woman and feminist in favor of the winning side. She denounced the ideals that we were fighting for, which became very destructive to our club’s survival. 
           My two personal experiences involving my high school principal and my teacher sponsor clarify sociological concepts such as hegemonic masculinity, woman as other, and defensive othering. These ideas create a harmful environment for young women in high school because they diminish the woman’s identity and force her into submission. These ideas are so prevalent that young women will often create conflict within themselves, furthering the damage caused. This shame and control keep girls from realizing their full potential and coming into themselves. High school is still a toxic environment for young women, and much needs to be done to fix this. A first step is to understand the concepts that are inhibiting people from working together, and slowly breaking down barriers. Then, we can work towards making a more understanding and inclusive society.

Religion and Work in the 21st Century
	In his book, 21 Lessons for the 21st Century, Harari analyzes many different aspects of society and provides his input on why he believes they either contribute to or diminish aspects of society. Some of his ideas include ideas about religion, Artificial Intelligence (AI), terrorism, and many more. He provides an interesting perspective on these ideas and goes into depth about each one. Two of Harari’s main points are about religion and its effect on societal issues and the role it plays in society as well as the work ethic/ introduction of AI into society and how that changes the way people work. Both topics are commonly talked about in sociology, as well as in the readings we did in class. Those are the topics that will be focused on throughout this essay. 
	Durkheim, Maryanski, and Turner evaluate the essence of religion in our earliest time in society. Together, they analyze the point that religion was needed in society to develop emotional intelligence, cognitive ability, and the fundamental categories of thought as well as forming the first social groups in society. Religion played a key role in forming the fundamental categories of thought in our society by forcing the earliest humans to form their own beliefs about something and create a structure in which to live their lives. Durkheim describes this concept as collective effervescence. Religions were created from this fundamental category of thought since multiple people believed in the same ideas. Once they formed these religious ideas, social groups were then formed based off religious beliefs and understandings. This helped to shape society in the earliest time because people were put into social groups and social standings which in turn created social hierarchies. In the earlier periods of society, this was important because it created structure, showed people the “way of life”, and basically told them where they belonged in society. Over time, religious social groups have been questioned as to whether they help society or hurt it. 
	Harari believes that these religious groups have over time hurt society and caused hostility within it, leading to conflict and instability. While Harari does agree with Durkheim, Maryanski, and Turner that religion does create social groups and hierarchies in a society, he does not agree with the idea that they are necessary or beneficial for a society in the twenty-first century. On page 138 of his book, he states that “unfortunately, all of this [issues within religion and economic problems] really makes traditional religions part of humanity’s problem, not part of the remedy.” He elaborates on this by stating that religions have been turned to be used against the people in government, rather than for the people. They are used to separate people, not unify them. This is where he would begin to disagree with Durkheim, Maryanski, and Turner because they believed that religion was a necessary part of society to create structure. While Harari wouldn’t completely disagree with this, he also wouldn’t completely agree. He states that, “…nationalism and religion still divide our human civilization into different and often hostile camps.” Harari believes that religion has been turned into a negative construct that causes hostility rather than a unifying subject in society. However, he does say that religion isn’t all negative because it can help country leaders to make economic decisions based on their belief systems. Harari would probably disagree with Durkheim, Maryanski, and Turner in their broad idea that religion is a positive aspect of society because he believes that overall, it causes more negativity in society than it does positivity. 
	The second commonly talked about idea in sociology is work. In Karl Marx’s “Estranged Labour”, he states that work under capitalism is not beneficial to society because in time it causes people to give up their true self and be forced into labor. He says that they become forced to be a part of competition rather than working for themselves, like they used to in earlier times of society. Because of the competition created by work under capitalism, people tend to lose their true identity and work ethic. They work for societal approval, rather than approval by themselves and their belief system. He would also say that the nature of human beings has become unique because people almost willingly give up themselves and their beliefs to fit into society and become a product of labor under capitalism. Marx states that over time, this causes alienation within a society and withing your essence of self because people give away their happiness and true self to fit in with the ideas of capitalism and work under capitalism. 
	Harari believes something like Marx, but not because of capitalism. In his book, Harari discusses the future of labor due to the implementing of Artificial Intelligence systems in our society. He attempts to warn the reader that AI systems will take away jobs and take away motivation to work. Harari believes that once AI systems can take over jobs, this will cause panic and chaos because people won’t have to work anymore. This in turn will lead to a lack of motivation and the want to work. On page 55, Harari states, “Once AI makes better decisions than we do about careers and perhaps even relationships, our concept of humanity and of life will perhaps have to change.” This is an important idea to bring up because this summarizes Harari’s main point of AI’s and the work environment in society. A good example from class that relates to this view is the Jarus video, which is about a family that allowed an AI system to completely control their lives, such as chores, locations, TV time, etc. Harari would not support this lifestyle because the children will be raised to believe everything is done for them and they can rely on an AI system about when to do certain things and what is right and wrong. If the AI systems are implemented into society in this type of way, no one will be able to think for themselves anymore, causing their true self to be the ‘true self’ of the AI system, not their own. 
	While Harari and Marx discuss different aspects of work in society, they have similar or complementary beliefs about societies view of work. In Marx’s viewpoint, he believes that humans have lost their true selves while working under capitalism. In Harari’s viewpoint, he believes that humans will have to reevaluate their sense of self if AI’s take over human jobs. These viewpoints are similar and complementary because both change the sense of self that humanity has and will cause a huge shift in society. Marx would say that capitalism caused the shift in the sense of self of society and Harari would say the same about AI’s. Both believe that these interferences in society led to negative outputs rather than positive outputs. They would also both say that the work in society should not be influenced by these factors because society will not be the same with this occurring. If the true self of the people is put at risk, humanity will completely change and not be able to turn around to revert to the old ways of the work force. 
	Harari would support the concept of work brought about by Marx but not the concept of religion brought about by Maryanski, Turner, and Durkheim for a few reasons. For one, the concept of Marx is more modernized, and Harari continuously suggests lessons throughout his book to try to prepare us for the future of the twenty-first century. Marx’s idea about work in society is like Harari’s because he relates it to what can happen in the future. The idea about religion by Maryanski, Turner, and Durkheim doesn’t necessarily grow with the future of society, but rather acts as one idea over time. They’re idea about religion doesn’t provide a modern viewpoint and suggests one main idea, rather than relating it to the future of society or modernizing it to how society is today. This makes a major impact on Harari not fully agreeing with their stance on religion because his stance relates more to the current and future impacts of society. 
	In conclusion, while Harari does not completely agree with the ideas brought about by Durkheim, Marynaski, and Turner regarding religion, he would agree with the ideas brought about by Marx regarding the work system in society. Harari believes that religion is not completely benefitting society, and in the long run could damage the way that society works because it creates hostility and negative social groups in our society. He also believes that the work system in society could be completely damaged by AI’s, which in turn would damage the idea of our true self and would cause our true self to be thoughts created by an algorithm program rather than our own thoughts. Harari brings many interesting points into common ideas discussed in sociology and causes readers to question ideas that they thought they stood firmly on. The sociologists mentioned (Durkheim, Marx, Maryanski, and Turner), all have very sound and traditional views on society, while Harari comes in to question these sound views and provide a more updated side to them. Harari questions these views in an effort to predict and assist humanities future and provide a modern stance on many issues and situations occurring in society. Overall, Harari would agree with many perspectives of sociologists, however, also would disagree, and challenge many perspectives of sociologists, which is not traditionally seen in society nowadays.

Capitalism is a system based on 5 core principles: private property, supply & demand, competition, freedom, and incentive. Private property can be anything from something physical like a house to something intangible like a patent or a brand. Supply & demand is the economic system put into place where there is a direct relationship between a price and how much is produced based on sales. Competition is related to the working field and any other possible jobs in which the best people rise to the top. Everyone wants to be at the top so it is a constant struggle to get there. Freedom is connected to a person's right to autonomy and choices. Finally, incentive regards to profit and making people strive to get that profit. People and companies will work harder and be more innovative and efficient to achieve that improved profit. A society that exists of these 5 aspects is a self-serving one. People within the society are encouraged to be independent and look out for themselves so that they can compete to be on top. This makes a series of impersonal exchanges and an excess of intangible assets. The depersonalization of an economy and those within it go hand-in-hand with McDonaldization and Rationalization. Both systems rely on anything but humanity and interpersonal communication. Though Capitalism has more equity seeing the more you wear the more you get, it does have the habit of developing systems in which people do not interact. Isolation is a key component of Capitalism. 
Marxism mixed with Capitalism finalizes the concept that isolation is inevitable when people are exposed to the 5 pillars of Capitalism. The Marxist idea that humans are so susceptive to change based on what they are surrounded by makes Capitalism the key to coding someone's manner and habits. Each of the five pillars affects social habits in different ways, but competition and incentives are more likely to cause isolation and self-serving behavior. Competition causes people to directly go up against one another and struggle to get to the top. There can only be so many on top, so it causes tension and individualism. Incentive has many forms, money, success, and any other kinds of profit available. So, different people will strive and improve things for different reasons, so what one person does for their incentive might oppose another person's way of receiving their incentive. The culmination of the two creates the ultimate individualist structure in this bigger society. Marxism is a smaller scale of a big society/economy where people can be connected to their work and surroundings more easily. This encourages a herd mentality and community, versus a competitive struggle to determine who will be on top.
In conclusion, human nature is easily changed and can be rewired based on the necessity to survive and thrive. Capitalism has specific aspects in which they can isolate all the natural survival instincts to then cause people to be more self-interested and individualistic. Though Capitalism is effective, it does oppose the groupthink aspect of social nature.

Equal Pay
	Are women and men truly being paid equally in current-day America? It would be easy to say the answer is yes, they are paid equally, especially after the Equal Pay Act of 1963 was passed and enforced, however, if you really dig deep into some companies you would be surprised to see this is not always upheld. While there are many different variables and circumstances that can play a role in a person's average income different studies have shown that women and men are in fact not paid equally at all companies. On average a woman completing the same job that a man is, holding the same level of degree, would only be paid about 80% of what that man would be paid. However, because of the vast number of variables that can affect a person’s salary the issue regarding equal pay in America has not been an easy battle to fight. 
	The biggest misconception regarding equal pay discrimination is that it does not occur in America and only happens in other countries. Another common misconception about equal pay discrimination is that it only affects people who work full-time at large companies. Research has shown that the smallest gender pay gap is for both part-time and full-time workers between the ages of 25 and 34. Women who are between the ages of 25 and 34, on average, make 93 cents for every dollar that a man in this age group makes, whereas workers age 16+ (excluding ages 25-34) on average make 84 cents for every dollar a man of the same age makes. To make matters worse, Black and Latina women in America make even less than white women in America. 
	My mom’s friend, who will be named Emily, experienced a similar situation except unlike me, Emily was working at her company full-time receiving a salary rather than hourly pay. Emily had been working at this company for 19 years when she got promoted from “team member” to manager after her previous manager left. Her previous manager was a man who had only been with this company for about 5 years before he left. Emily had her master's, a higher degree in school than her previous manager who only had a bachelor's degree. When Emily got promoted to manager, she expected to be getting the same salary her previous manager did when he started working as a manager. This however was not the case. Emily found out she was making 30,000 dollars less than what her previous manager made annually, even though she had been at the company for 14 more years than he was and she even had a higher level of education than he possessed. Both of these situations go to show that not only do women who work full-time and receive a salary get discriminated against when it comes to equal pay, but part-time hourly pay workers do as well. 
	Discrimination against women regarding equal pay most of the time spawns from men who believe, or have been taught, that the male sex is more powerful and is placed higher than women in a social hierarchy. Brett G. Stoudt conducted research regarding hegemonic masculinity in an all-boys school to see if the lack of women and women as authoritative figures had an effect on the way these young boys viewed women. This study was taken place in an all-boys school called Rockport, located in an upper-middle to upper-class region. This study was distributed to 148 boys who attended Rockport. Hegemonic masculinity as described in this research paper is the idea and practice that validates the idea that men belong above women in a social hierarchy. Stoudt's research concluded that at Rockport hegemonic masculinity was taught and reinforced through their schooling curriculum. The effect of this on the teenage boys who attend this school was shown through a conversation with David and Brian, two boys who went to school at Rockport. Both David and Brian claimed they viewed girls as a mother or a friend because they were better at the emotional and caring aspects of life. This unfortunately places women in a subordinated position in these teenage boys' minds without them even realizing it. 
	As mentioned above the teaching of hegemonic masculinity is very common throughout society and plays a major role in the social hierarchy which places men above women. This hierarchy is one of the major issues that have caused this unequal pay between men and women. If I were to have had a female supervisor who was in charge of the hourly pay it is much more likely that I would have received the pay I was promised while I was being interviewed. There is a small chance that she would have started women lifeguards out at the base pay because she believed “men are stronger than women so in conclusion men are more capable and proficient in this job” just like my male supervisor believed.

As the social hierarchy of men being placed above women has decreased so has the gap between the average pay of men and women, however, there is still a fairly large difference. Women making on average 93 cents for every dollar a man makes may not seem like a huge gap in pay, but over time this pay difference adds up. The average annual wage in America is about 51,916 dollars. If a man made that amount in a year a woman would only make around 48,281 dollars. The Beauty Truth

What enables the power difference between men and women within society? These questions and more have been asked over and over by women trying to come up with logical solutions to the disparities that they face compared to men.
